<div id="review_3709142721" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3709142721" />
    <a title="Holly" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4511019-holly"><img alt="Holly" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616528580p2/4511019.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3709142721?book_show_action=true">Dec 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Holly" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Holly" href="/user/show/4511019-holly">Holly</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=audiobook">audiobook</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=biggest-disappointment">biggest-disappointment</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=no-thank-you">no-thank-you</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=fantasy-or-sci-fi">fantasy-or-sci-fi</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=made-me-cry">made-me-cry</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=girls-who-rule">girls-who-rule</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=slow-burn">slow-burn</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=i-ship-them">i-ship-them</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4511019-holly?shelf=i-m-keeping-the-headcanon">i-m-keeping-the-headcanon</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
                  <em>
                    This review has been hidden because it contains spoilers. To view it,
                    <a href="#" onclick="Effect.toggle(&#39;reviewTextContainer3709142721&#39;); return false;">click here.</a>
                  </em>
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3709142721" class="readable"
                    style="display:none"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1541380979620736773">Hate this book but I still <a href='https://open.spotify.com/playlist/5sF06Xl3qFgi9iUcazRmrH' rel='nofollow noopener'>made a Helene Aquilla playlist</a> because I love her.<br/><br/>If my review could be a sound, it would be endless screaming.<br/><br/>I first read An Ember in the Ashes in 2017 and immediately bought a Torch Against the Night. I eagerly awaited the release of Reaper and I loved it even more than the first two. You can imagine how excited I was, waiting for this book to be released. And then it was terrible.<br/><br/>This book was filled with plot holes, quite frankly ridiculous situations and an overw</span>
  <span id="freeText1541380979620736773" style="display:none">Hate this book but I still <a href="https://open.spotify.com/playlist/5sF06Xl3qFgi9iUcazRmrH" rel="nofollow noopener">made a Helene Aquilla playlist</a> because I love her.<br /><br />If my review could be a sound, it would be endless screaming.<br /><br />I first read An Ember in the Ashes in 2017 and immediately bought a Torch Against the Night. I eagerly awaited the release of Reaper and I loved it even more than the first two. You can imagine how excited I was, waiting for this book to be released. And then it was terrible.<br /><br />This book was filled with plot holes, quite frankly ridiculous situations and an overwhelming number of YA tropes in the worst possible way.<br /><br />Elias used to be one of my favourite characters but he became so, so boring. I was excited to see how his character would develop throughout the series, especially as he was dealing with the conflict of being a Blackcliff student and being friends with people like Dex and Helene, and his upbringing with Tribe Saif. But we did NOT get character development. Elias of books three and four is so boring I couldn't cope. It just felt like the same drawn-out line over and over again. Also, it did nothing to advance his or Laia's arc. It was a really dull way of creating tension between the two of them. The soul catcher plot did nothing other than bloat two books that did not need it. Yes, we can argue about the information he got from his grandmother but there were so many arguably more interesting ways that information could have been acquired. In this book he was either moaning about his job, moaning about his love for Laia, or moaning about how he couldn't remember anything. He also conveniently got his memories back at the start of the book. I really like Elias but it was hard to care about him when his character stopped developing in Torch, and certainly in Reaper. It's such a shame because he's actually really funny in the first two books. And even in Reaper I could deal with him. But it's like everything that made him interesting was gone.<br /><br />I like Laia. Or I did like Laia. She's come a long way since Embers. And I feel like in Reaper in particular she really shone. She was on the move and doing things. But here, a lot of it was just her moping after Elias and ignoring advice from absolutely everyone. She let a jinn take her capture, and constantly ignored Rehmat when she advised that this might not be the smartest idea. Where is the Laia who in Embers looked the Empire in the face and decided that her brother's life and freedom was more important to her than her fear of the Empire and what might happen if she stood up to it. She was astoundingly selfish in this book and focussed only on her lust for Elias. I get it, you want him and I'm totally here for women who want to fuck their boyfriend, but the world is also ending. She did nothing in this book. Nothing at all apart from make bad decision after bad decision and then get praised by literally every other character for being wonderful and the gift to the world. She acquired powers out of nowhere and didn't even use them in a sensible way. I grew to hate her. Hate feels a little unfair, but I really didn't enjoy her chapters and it was such a shame because I loved how she'd always been this girl who wasn't necessarily anything special. But she was good and fierce in her own way. But now she's got so many powers and they came out of nowhere, and it didn't work for me.<br /><br />Talking of stupid decisions, why did Tas come back? How did Musa even know about him then find him? Like, why? Why would Musa think "Hmm, I know. We're in a war, so it's only logical to bring a child back from where they're safe to experience the danger." I adore Musa, but really. This was one of many ridiculous and poorly explained, no wait not explained at all, choices in this book.<br /><br />The nightbringer made me want to punch something. Not because he was an evil villain, but because I couldn't understand the point of any of it. What was the point of releasing the jinn if he's just going to kill them off? It went from him seeking revenge, in a twisted but understandable way, to randomly wanting to end the entire world. What was the point in any of what he's been up to for the last thousand years if he just wants to destroy the world? Why not get on with it instead of freeing his people? Why not kill himself, if he realises that his suffering alone can make the sea fill the world? This didn't make any sense. I really liked his backstory of being motivated and ultimately twisted by love. But this book changed all that.<br /><br />Keris, who was the real villain imo, got ignored, and when her story was addressed it was barely skimmed over. Keris was one of the most interesting characters in this series. She is chilling and cruel, she tried to kill her own son multiple times. But she also watched out for Avitas when he was a Blackcliff student. She took revenge on the other Masks who murdered her lover. And yet she practically lay down and died like a baby in the final battle. I do not believe it, not for one tiny second. I was so disappointed because I felt like in Reaper in particular we'd really begun to understand Keris and her history. There were so many more opportunities to explore that and yet it didn't happen.<br /><br />Helene, out of all the characters, has come the longest way since the first book. She supported an empire which enslaves people and treats them cruelly and couldn't see that loyalty is more than loyalty to her country. But in Embers she is not only dealing with the demands of the trials, to see who will be the next emperor. She is also the only female student at Blackcliff. The men around her ignore that she is a woman when it is convenient for them but are quite happy to use it against her. She's often the victim of unwanted touching and objectification. It's easy to see how she became closed off to other people, following orders and not wanting to stray from the path ahead of her. The men, while still threatened by punishment, always had more licence to be themselves than she did. And none of them recognise that. Even Elias, who is her best friend, would often make comments about her body in the first book. And yet she takes it because she has to. She hurts and just wants to be loved, but time and time again she gets back up after she's been pushed away and rejected by everyone around her. Helene's strength and growth is what kept me loving this series. She is such a compelling character and I was so excited to see how her story would end. By this book she's been through so much. She is still struggling to open up to people because she has experienced absolutely dreadful losses. Slowly, with the help of the people around her, Helene is learning that she can open up. She sees that love isn't guaranteed, and there are moments when she lets other people in.<br /><br />Avitas Harper is one of my favourite characters in the series. I know some people struggled to connect with him, but I really appreciated how quiet and calm he was. He knows what Helene needs, he's not afraid to tell her she's making the wrong decision, but he also supports her and lets her make her own choices. Honestly, compared to the back-and-forth toxicity of Laia and Elias's relationship, watching Helene and Avitas was a joy. It was sweet and sad, because Helene was struggling to open up. But I felt like I was seeing a future between actual adults, dealing with adult things like running a country, balancing responsibilities and trying not to get your heart trampled on at the same time. I really wanted to see their relationship addressed in more detail. They both have to be dealing with some trauma. Avitas was forced to torture Helene in Torch, and that must have haunted both of them. So I'd have loved to see that brought up in some way and put to rest so they could both move on with their lives together. We...sort of got that. Ok, we didn't actually get to see the torture issue addressed unfortunately, but there were moments when we saw the growth of their relationship. And god knows, they both deserved happiness. Sadly though Avitas was really pushed to the side in this book. He went from a very complex character to Helene's love interest. It was really disappointing because again, in Reaper, we'd seen so much more of his character development and he had so much to offer.<br /><br />The deaths.<br /><br />Faris. Poor Faris. He's such a good guy. He sticks by Helene, he encourages her to make the right choices. He hates having to hunt Elias in Torch. And through it all he remains cheerful and tries to be a good friend to all. His death gutted me, but I could at least understand it. He gave his life for his friend, for the Blood Shrike, to let Helene live. This felt true to his character. And it made sense, given where it happened in the book. <br /><br />Livia. On the one hand I understand it because Keris is an evil bitch and she wanted to weaken Helene. So she kills Livia and Nikla to get to Helene and Musa. It did feel cruel though, especially after all Helene had been through. This was also the beginning of Helene suddenly not being able to use her powers. Why? This was never explained. She's healed people with horrific injuries before, but in this book, when people she loves are dying, she doesn't. It did not fit with her character or the powers she is supposed to have. And what was all that with Keris letting the baby live?<br /><br />The final battle, if we can even call it that, is my least favourite part of the book. Keris was killed far too easily. All it took was to mention her mother, that was it. So Quin could never have mentioned it before? Elias could never have found a way to throw it in her face? None of them? And you really expect me to believe that Keris who is so, so cruel, would break like that? It was a giant anti-climax. Suddenly she's there fighting, she murders someone, she laughs at Helene, Helene says one word and Keris gives up. It was utterly ridiculous after she'd been built up as this extremely skilled and cruel person for the entire series. I'm furious that she got a happy ever after. She did not deserve it. Not after everything she did.<br /><br />I found the resolution with the nightbringer unsatisfactory. In the end he agreed to be chained and wanted his story told. Well, all that murder really makes sense now, or not. All Laia did was stood around and had a chat with him for five minutes. I felt like this really took away from everything Laia has had to do, and all the struggles she's been through. It made her character kind of pointless, because essentially Rehmat pops up and magically solves everything. What was the point in any of this! What even was the point of Rehmat. If the Jinn are supposed to be able to see the future why did she put herself into the blood line of humans for a thousand years, hoping one of them would wake her up. This is such a flimsy reason for her it is almost funny, except it makes me want to bash my head against the wall.<br /><br />Both Darin and Harper's deaths were unnecessary. Yes I understand that this is part of war. People die. This is also a book that we read because we hope that we are going to enjoy the experience and get a satisfactory ending to the series. Killing those two characters so close to the end of the book felt like it was for shock value and nothing else. I absolutely hate authors doing this. Kill a character because it serves a purpose, not just for the sake of it. These deaths served no purpose at all other than to make readers sob at the end of the series. All the drama with Keris and the Nightbringer had been resolved way too easily, so she had to throw something else in. Ultimately it's a sign of shitty writing. And I hate saying it because I'd loved these books. But this entire book was a complete shit show. It could have still ended with the same number of deaths, if those deaths have been written well. I can respect an author that kills my favourite characters if they do it in a way that is meaningful and part of a gripping plot. But for half of the book there was no plot and all of the characters were bland, and when there was something resembling a plot it was completely pointless and didn't even make sense.<br /><br />Laia could have used her powers to tell Darin she was all good, and Avitas is a fucking mask. He's not going to let his armour slip and then take two knives. Give me a break.<br /><br />It meant that Elias and Laia got to have their happy ending, and Helene had nothing. Nothing. I read the chapter where Harper dies and had to stop because I wasn't sure that I'd read it right. It didn't make sense for so many reasons. What was the point of Keris looking out for him if she was just going to kill him then. What was the point of Helene going to fight her if she knew that Mirra was alive, which also felt like a massively convenient plot device. Why didn't Helene sing his song in her head, which she can absolutely do to heal him. If we look at the mechanics and magic used previously, there is literally no reason why she couldn't have healed him. I understand that she was also injured, but within not much time she was up and walking around so it would have been possible. And you expect me to believe that Helene, strong, fierce, determined, loyal Helene would give up on him that quickly? She ran back into a battle in Reaper to pull him to safety, so no, she would not have dropped his hand. She’d have fought through the pain and sang his song in her head even if it killed her. Again, she could have killed him and I might have respected it if the plot had actually been good.<br /><br />I'm going to talk about colonialism now because some readers (I'm looking at you book Twitter), have said that Helene deserved all of this because she's a coloniser. Colonialism wrecks everyone's lives in the end except for a tiny few, and that point was illustrated so well throughout the series. If that was Sabaa's intention, why, in the end, was the Empire not dismantled? Helene is given the job of running the Empire. Yes, it makes her miserable. But one character having a miserable life doesn't actually fix the problem, the problem is the system. Why not have a decent cast of characters live, and build a fair, more equal government? Some kind of council where there is no familial succession. Where everyone has a voice?<br /><br />The Empire has now been transferred to the Aquilla line. And whilst Helene has realised how damaging the Empire is, who's to say in three emperors time that person will continue fair treatment of Tribespeople and Scholars? That line of Martial succession continues. I'm actually ok with Helene becoming empress because she's the only one who worked during the last two books, but seeing as people are using this as the reason why her life should have been destroyed I felt I had to address it. Literally nothing has changed by the end of the series. Helene's going to be more fair, but there's nothing to stop everything going back to how it was. And I don't actually believe Helene would be ok emotionally after everything she's been through. I honestly can't see her coping with the demands of running the empire and not wanting to hurt herself because she's young and essentially her whole life has been destroyed.<br /><br />If you like Helene, if you care about Helene and Harper, if you enjoy the fact that Laia is an ordinary girl dealing with terrible things, and if you hate but also are fascinated by the evil and twisted Keris, do not read this book.<br /><br />If you are here to see Laia and Elias get their happy ever after, regardless of whether they, particularly Elias, has done anything to deserve it, I suppose you'll be happy. But if you care about anything else this book is a disaster. If you like magical systems that aren't explained in the slightest and radically change in the last book for plot convenience, but also abandon characters at crucial moments, go right ahead and eat this up. But if you want to read about a well-developed system where the characters actually earn their victories and where the plot is consistent, give this a miss.<br /><br />In the end, I stayed for the politics. I loved Embers because it was about Laia fighting this awful system. It was about Elias trying to defect. And Helene, who is a complex, morally ambiguous but ultimately kind and good character. After book two I was here for Helene and some parts of Laia, particularly when Laia was trying to get allies. But in the end, the chaotic and poorly planned magical plot took over and ruined what could have been an incredible series without it.<br /><br />I could just TLDR this and say Helene deserved better as did we as readers and this was astoundingly awful.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1541380979620736773" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


